# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: circleci
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:circleci/circleci] In total this is $315 million in funding.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI acquired Distiller in 2014, Vamp in 2021, and Ponicode in 2022.
[src:circleci/circleci] In 2013, CircleCI suffered a major data breach due to its provider MongoHQ, but was able to quickly respond and replace its security keys, resulting in almost no lost customers.
[src:circleci/circleci] In August 2019, there was a data breach in a third-party analytics vendor account used by CircleCI.
[src:circleci/circleci] In January 2023, CircleCI announced a recent system breach and advised customers to rotate "any and all secrets" stored in CircleCI.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI monitors GitHub, GitHub Enterprise, and Atlassian Bitbucket repositories and launches builds for each new commit.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI automatically tests builds in either Docker containers or virtual machines and deploys passing builds to target environments.
[src:circleci/circleci] A dashboard and API allow tracking the status of builds and metrics related to builds.
[src:circleci/circleci] A Slack integration notifies teams if issues arise.
[src:circleci/circleci] SSH support allows locally running jobs, and security measures prevent tampering.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI also offers a workflow approval feature that pauses the job(s) until manual approval is given.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI supports Go, Java, Ruby, Python, Scala, Node.js, PHP, Haskell, and any other language that runs on Linux or macOS.
[src:circleci/circleci] The company offers a managed cloud service with a free tier available.
[src:circleci/circleci] The platform can also be self-hosted on a private server (behind a corporate firewall), or as a private deployment in the cloud.
[src:circleci/circleci] The cloud service was initially written from scratch but now uses HashiCorp's Nomad and Kubernetes.
[src:circleci/circleci] The cloud service can be set up within minutes, but is less customizable than Jenkins.
[src:circleci/circleci] Orbs are shareable snippets of YAML that can be used to simplify CircleCI builds and perform deployments.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI had integrations with 45 partners as of 2019.
[src:circleci/circleci] CircleCI's target deployment environments include Amazon Web Services, Heroku, Azure, Google Compute Engine, Docker images, and virtual Linux, Android, Windows, or macOS machines with VMware.
[src:circleci/circleci] In 2018 CircleCI's `config.yml` was the fastest growing YAML file on GitHub.
[src:circleci/circleci] The proprietary configuration syntax introduces vendor lock-in, meaning that switching CI services requires rewriting the pipeline.
[src:circleci/concepts] This guide introduces some basic concepts to help you understand how CircleCI manages your CI/CD pipelines.
[src:circleci/concepts] In CircleCI, *concurrency* refers to utilizing multiple containers to run multiple jobs at the same time.
[src:circleci/concepts] Concurrency is different from CircleCI *parallelism*, which splits the tests of a single job across multiple containers.
[src:circleci/concepts] To keep the system stable for all CircleCI customers, we use different soft concurrency limits on each of the Resource Classes for different executors.
[src:circleci/concepts] If you experience queueing on your jobs, you may be hitting these limits.
[src:circleci/concepts] Customers on annual plans can request an increase to those limits at no extra charge.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Concurrency page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI believes in *configuration as code*.
[src:circleci/concepts] A single file called `config.yml` orchestrates your entire CI/CD process.
[src:circleci/concepts] This file lives in a folder called `.circleci` at the root of your project and defines the entire pipeline.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can adapt your CircleCI configuration to fit the different needs of your project.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Introduction to YAML Configurations page for basic guidance.
[src:circleci/concepts] For a full overview of what is possible in a configuration file, see the Configuration Reference page.
[src:circleci/concepts] Contexts provide a mechanism for securing and sharing environment variables across projects.
[src:circleci/concepts] You define environment variables as name/value pairs, and CircleCI injects them at runtime.
[src:circleci/concepts] Add environment variables to the context.
[src:circleci/concepts] Use the `context` key in the workflows section of a project’s configuration file to give access to the environment variables stored in the context.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Using Contexts page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] Persist data to move data between jobs and speed up your build.
[src:circleci/concepts] Artifacts persist data after a workflow completes and provide longer-term storage of the outputs of your build process.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Storing Build Artifacts page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] A cache stores a file or directory of files such as dependencies or source code in object storage.
[src:circleci/concepts] To speed up the build, each job may contain special steps for caching dependencies from previous jobs.
[src:circleci/concepts] If you need to clear your cache, refer to the Caching Dependencies page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] For more information see the Caching Dependencies page.
[src:circleci/concepts] Workspaces are a workflow-aware storage mechanism.
[src:circleci/concepts] A workspace stores data unique to the job, which downstream jobs may need.
[src:circleci/concepts] Each workflow has a temporary workspace associated with it.
[src:circleci/concepts] Use the workspace to pass along unique data built during a job to other jobs in the same workflow.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Using Workspaces page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] Docker layer caching (DLC) caches the individual layers of Docker images built during your CircleCI jobs.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI uses any unchanged layers on subsequent runs, rather than rebuilding the image each time.
[src:circleci/concepts] In the `.circleci/config.yml` snippet below, the `build_elixir` job builds an image using the `ubuntu-2004:202104-01` Dockerfile.
[src:circleci/concepts] Adding `docker_layer_caching: true` below the `machine` executor key ensures CircleCI saves each Docker image layer as the Elixir image is built.
[src:circleci/concepts] On subsequent commits, if the Dockerfile has not changed, DLC pulls each Docker image layer from cache during the `build Elixir image` step and the image builds faster.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Docker Layer Caching page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] Instead of manually creating your configuration for each CircleCI project, you can generate this configuration dynamically, based on specific pipeline parameters or file paths.
[src:circleci/concepts] Dynamic configuration is helpful where your team is working on a monorepo (or a single repository).
[src:circleci/concepts] Dynamic configuration allows you to trigger builds from *specific* parts of your project, rather than rebuilding everything each time.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Dynamic Configuration page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] Each separate job defined within your configuration runs in a unique execution environment, known as executors.
[src:circleci/concepts] An executor can be a Docker container, or a virtual machine running Linux, Windows, or macOS.
[src:circleci/concepts] In some of these instances, you can set up an environment using GPU, or Arm.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI also provides a machine-based and container-based self-hosted runner solution.
[src:circleci/concepts] An *image* is a packaged system that includes instructions for creating a running container or virtual machine, and you can define an image for each executor.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI provides a range of images for use with the Docker executor, called *convenience images* (details in the images section).
[src:circleci/concepts] The first image listed in the `.circleci/config.yml` file defines the primary container.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI executes commands in the primary container.
[src:circleci/concepts] The Docker executor spins up a container with a Docker image.
[src:circleci/concepts] The machine executor spins up a complete Ubuntu virtual machine image.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can add further images to spin up secondary/service containers.
[src:circleci/concepts] For added security when using the Docker executor and running Docker commands, use the `setup_remote_docker` key to spin up another Docker container in which to run these commands.
[src:circleci/concepts] For more information see the Running Docker Commands page.
[src:circleci/concepts] For more information, see the Execution Environments Overview page.
[src:circleci/concepts] An image is a packaged system that includes instructions for creating a running container.
[src:circleci/concepts] The first image listed in a `.circleci/config.yml` file defines the primary container.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI executes commands for jobs in the primary container, using the Docker or machine executor.
[src:circleci/concepts] The **Docker executor** spins up a container with a Docker image.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI maintains Convenience Images for popular languages on Docker Hub.
[src:circleci/concepts] The **machine executor** spins up a complete Ubuntu virtual machine image, giving you full access to OS resources and complete control over the job environment.
[src:circleci/concepts] For more information, see the Using Machine page.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the CircleCI Images page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] Jobs are the building blocks of your configuration.
[src:circleci/concepts] Jobs are collections of steps, which run commands/scripts as required.
[src:circleci/concepts] Each job must declare an executor that is either `docker`, `machine`, `windows`, or `macos`.
[src:circleci/concepts] For `docker` you must Specify an Image to use for the primary container.
[src:circleci/concepts] For `macos` you must specify an Xcode Version.
[src:circleci/concepts] For `windows` you must use the Windows Orb.
[src:circleci/concepts] For more information, see the Jobs and Steps page.
[src:circleci/concepts] Orbs are reusable snippets of code that help automate repeated processes, accelerate project setup, and help you to integrate with third-party tools.
[src:circleci/concepts] The illustration in the Configuration section showing an example Java configuration simplifies using orbs.
[src:circleci/concepts] The following illustration demonstrates a simplified configuration with the Maven orb.
[src:circleci/concepts] Here, the orb sets up a default executor that can execute steps with Maven and run a common job (`maven/test`).
[src:circleci/concepts] See Using Orbs for details on how to use orbs in your configuration and an introduction to orb design.
[src:circleci/concepts] Visit the Orbs registry to search for orbs to help simplify your configuration.
[src:circleci/concepts] The more tests your project involves, the longer it takes for them to complete on a single machine.
[src:circleci/concepts] Using *test splitting* and *parallelism*, you can spread your tests across a specified number of separate executors.
[src:circleci/concepts] You conventionally define test suites at the Job level in your `.circleci/config.yml` file.
[src:circleci/concepts] The `parallelism` key specifies how CircleCI sets up independent executors to run the steps of a job.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can use the `circleci tests` commands to split your test suite to run across your parallel executors.
[src:circleci/concepts] To run a job’s steps in parallel, set the `parallelism` key to a value greater than `1`.
[src:circleci/concepts] See Test Splitting and Parallelism page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] A CircleCI pipeline is the full set of processes you run when you trigger work on your projects.
[src:circleci/concepts] Pipelines encompass your workflows, which in turn coordinate your jobs.
[src:circleci/concepts] Pipelines are defined in your project configuration file.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Pipelines Overview page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] For GitHub OAuth app and Bitbucket Cloud accounts, a *project* in CircleCI is tied to, and shares the name of the associated code repository in your VCS.
[src:circleci/concepts] For GitHub App, GitLab SaaS and self-managed and Bitbucket Data Center users, a *project* in CircleCI is standalone.
[src:circleci/concepts] You create a project and then connect your code (stored in your GitHub, GitLab or Bitbucket Data Center repository) to that project.
[src:circleci/concepts] Select **Projects** in the CircleCI web app sidebar to enter the projects dashboard.
[src:circleci/concepts] On the dashboard, you can set up and follow any project you have access to.
[src:circleci/concepts] If you do not see the **Create project** button you are in a `GitHub` or `Bitbucket` organization.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can use the **Set up** button to start building your project on CircleCI.
[src:circleci/concepts] For more information on organization types, see the Users, Organizations, and Integrations Guide page.
[src:circleci/concepts] A resource class is a configuration option that allows you to control available compute resources (CPU and RAM) for your jobs.
[src:circleci/concepts] When you specify an execution environment for a job, CircleCI sets a default resource class value for the environment *unless* you define the resource class in your configuration.
[src:circleci/concepts] Define the resource class as best practice, instead of relying on a default.
[src:circleci/concepts] The example below shows how to define a resource class in the Docker execution environment.
[src:circleci/concepts] Pricing and plans information for the various resource classes can be found on the Resource classes product page.
[src:circleci/concepts] The `resource_class` key is also used to configure a Self-Hosted Runner Instance.
[src:circleci/concepts] For full details on both uses of resource classes, see the Resource Class Overview page.
[src:circleci/concepts] Steps are collections of the executable commands required to complete your job.
[src:circleci/concepts] For example, the `checkout` step (which is a built-in step available across all CircleCI projects) checks out the source code for a job over SSH.
[src:circleci/concepts] The `run` step allows you to run custom commands, such as executing the command `make test`, using a non-login shell by default.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can also define commands outside the job declaration, making them reusable across your configuration.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Jobs and Steps page for more information.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI sets up roles differently depending on your Organization Type.
[src:circleci/concepts] To check your organization type, check your organization slug at **Overview**.
[src:circleci/concepts] For `circleci` type organizations, you set roles at the organization and project level.
[src:circleci/concepts] These roles are separate from permissions and roles in your version control system.
[src:circleci/concepts] For an overview of organization and project role permissions, see the Roles and Permissions Overview page.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Manage Roles and Permissions page for steps to add, remove, and change org and project level roles.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can also manage roles and permissions in Groups.
[src:circleci/concepts] CircleCI has various user roles with permissions inherited from VCS accounts.
[src:circleci/concepts] A workflow defines a list of jobs and their run order.
[src:circleci/concepts] You can run jobs concurrently, sequentially, on a schedule, or with a manual gate using an approval job.
[src:circleci/concepts] See the Using Workflows page for more information.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] This document is a reference for the CircleCI 2.x configuration keys that are used in the `.circleci/config.yml` file.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] You can see a complete `config.yml` in our full example.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The `version` field is intended to be used in order to issue warnings for deprecation or breaking changes.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The `setup` field enables you to conditionally trigger configurations from outside the primary `.circleci` parent directory, update pipeline parameters, or generate customized configurations.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Use the `orbs` key to reference or define reusable configuration blocks (orbs) for use in your configuration.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The following example uses the `node` orb that exists in the certified `circleci` namespace.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Refer to the Node orb page in the Orb Registry for more examples and information.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Public orbs are listed in the Orb Registry.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] A `command` defines a sequence of steps as a map to be executed in a job, enabling you to reuse a single command definition across multiple jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For more information see the Reusable Config Reference Guide.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Use the `parameters` key at the top level of your config to declare *pipeline parameters* for use in the configuration.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] See Pipeline Values and Parameters for usage details.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] This example declares a pipeline parameter named `image-tag` with a type of `string` and a default value of `current`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Once you have declared a pipeline parameter, you can pass a pipeline parameter value when triggering a pipeline via the API or from the CircleCI web app.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Executors define the execution environment where job steps run, letting you reuse a single executor definition across multiple jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you set more than one, CircleCI returns an error.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] See the Using Parameters in Executors section of the Reusing Config page for examples of parameterized executors.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] A Workflow is comprised of one or more uniquely named jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Jobs are specified in the `jobs` map, see Sample Config.yml for two examples of a `job` map.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The name of the job is the key in the map, and the value is a map describing the job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Each job consists of the job’s name as a key and a map as a value.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] A name must be unique and case-insensitive within the `jobs` list.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] In this example the job name is `my-job`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Options are `release`, `approval`, `no-op`, `build` (default).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If a type is not specified, the job defaults to a `build` type.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Jobs with the `release` type are used to Connect Your Pipeline Configuration to a deployment in the CircleCI deploys UI.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For full details, see the Deploys Overview page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The `no-op` type is used to configure a job that performs no actions and consumes no credits.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] `no-op` is commonly used to organize the order of operations within a workflow and make it easier to maintain.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Only the `type` is required for a `no-op` type job, no further job configuration is required.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For some examples of using `no-op` jobs, see the Orchestration Cookbook.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The `approval` type is used to configure a manual approval step.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] No `job` configuration is required or allowed for an `approval` type job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The `approval` type is most commonly configured within a workflow rather than under the top-level `jobs` key.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Only `approval` type jobs can have their `type` configured under `workflows`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] See type under workflows section for full details.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] A map of environment variable names and values.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For more information on defining and using environment variables, and the order of precedence governing the various ways they can be set, see the Environment Variables page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Configure job retention periods to control how long job data is kept.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Job retention specifically controls cache retention at the job level.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] This setting can be configured from 1 day to 15 days using string values (for example, "1d", "7d", "15d").
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Job retention reduces the organization-level retention from the default by automatically removing cache data after the specified period.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For more information on cache retention, see the Persisting Data Overview page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Use this feature to optimize test steps.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you set `parallelism` to N > 1, CircleCI sets up N independent executors, and each runs the job’s steps in parallel.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] You can use the CircleCI CLI to split your test suite across parallel containers so the job completes in a shorter time.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Job-level `parameters` can be used when calling a `job` in a `workflow`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] See Parameter Syntax for definition details.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] CircleCI offers several execution environments in which to run your jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] To specify an execution environment choose an *executor*, then specify an image and a resource class.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] An executor defines the underlying technology, environment, and operating system in which to run a job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Set up your jobs to run using the `docker` (Linux), `machine` (LinuxVM, Windows, GPU, Arm), or `macos` executor, then specify an image with the tools and packages you need, and a resource class.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Learn more about execution environments and executors in the Introduction to Execution Environments.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For a Primary Container, (the first container in the list) if neither `command` nor `entrypoint` is specified in the configuration, then any `ENTRYPOINT` and `COMMAND` in the image are ignored.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The primary container is typically only used for running the `steps` and not for its `ENTRYPOINT`, and an `ENTRYPOINT` may consume significant resources or exit prematurely.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] A Custom Image may disable this behavior and force the `ENTRYPOINT` to run.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] You can specify image versions using tags or digest.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] You can use any public images from any public Docker registry (defaults to Docker Hub).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Learn more about specifying images on the Using the Docker Execution Environment page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Some registries, Docker Hub, for example, may rate limit anonymous Docker pulls.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] We recommend that you authenticate to pull private and public images.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The username and password can be specified in the `auth` field.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] See Using Docker Authenticated Pulls for details.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Using an image hosted on AWS ECR requires authentication using AWS credentials.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The two configuration options are described in the following sections.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For steps to get set up with OIDC to pull images from AWS ECR, see the Pull an Image From AWS ECR With OIDC page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] By default, CircleCI uses the AWS credentials you provide by setting the `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` and `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` project environment variables.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Using an image hosted on GCP Artifact Registry requires authentication using GCP credentials, either via OIDC, or by setting environment variables.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For steps to get set up with OIDC to pull images from GCP Artifact Registry, see the Pull an Image From GCP Artifact Registry With OIDC page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] By default, CircleCI uses the GCP credentials you provide by setting the `GCP_OIDC_SERVICE_ACCOUNT`, `GCP_WORKLOAD_IDENTITY_POOL`, and `GCP_WORKLOAD_IDENTITY_PROVIDER` project environment variables or context environment variables.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] More information on the software available in each image can be found in our Discuss forum.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The machine executor supports Docker Layer Caching, which is useful when you are building Docker images during your job or Workflow.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you are using CircleCI Server, contact your system administrator for details of available Linux machine images.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] CircleCI supports running jobs on Android for testing and deploying Android applications.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The Android image can also be accessed using the Android orb.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For examples, refer to the Using Android Images With the Machine Executor page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] More information on what software is available in each image can be found in our Discuss forum.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Alternatively, use the Windows orb to manage your Windows execution environment.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For examples, see the Using the Windows Execution Environment page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you are using CircleCI Server, contact your system administrator for details of available Windows machine images.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] CircleCI supports running jobs on macOS, to allow you to build, test, and deploy apps for macOS, iOS, tvOS and watchOS.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] To run a job on a macOS virtual machine, add the `macos` key to the top-level configuration for your job and specify the version of Xcode to use.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Use workflows filtering to control which jobs run for which branches.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] The `resource_class` feature allows you to configure CPU and RAM resources for each job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Resource classes are available for each execution environment, as described in the tables below.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] A resource class is also used as a label to identify a pool of self-hosted runners and to route a job to that pool.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For full details on both uses, see the Resource Class Overview page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] We implement soft concurrency limits for each resource class to ensure our system remains stable for all customers.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you are on a Performance or Custom Plan and experience queuing for certain resource classes, it is possible you are hitting these limits.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Contact CircleCI support to request a raise on these limits for your account.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you do not specify a resource class, CircleCI uses a default value that can change.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Specify a resource class instead of relying on a default.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] Use the `resource_class` key to configure a Self-hosted Runner Instance.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] View what is supported under **OS/ARCH** for the latest tags.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] For example, `cimg/python` has `linux/amd64` and `linux/arm64`, which means Arm **is** supported.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] If you are working on CircleCI Server you can access the macOS execution environment using Self-hosted Runner.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] See the Available Linux GPU images section for the full list of available images.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p01] (2) *This resource requires review by our support team.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `steps` setting in a job is a list of single key/value pairs, the key of which indicates the step type.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The value may be either a configuration map or a string (depending on what that type of step requires).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `name` attribute is used by the UI for display purposes.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `command` attribute is specific to the `run` step and defines the command to execute.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Some steps may implement a shorthand semantic.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In its short form, the `run` step allows us to directly specify which `command` to execute as a string value.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In this case the step itself provides default suitable values for other attributes (`name` here has the same value as `command`, for example).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In this case, the `checkout` step checks out project source code into the job’s `working_directory`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Each built-in step is described in detail below.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Use the `run` step to invoke command-line programs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `run` step takes either a map of configuration values, or, when you call it in short-form, a string that serves as both the `command` and `name`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] CircleCI executes `run` commands using non-login shells by default, so you must explicitly source any `dotfiles` as part of the command.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Each `run` declaration represents a new shell.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] You can specify a multi-line `command` where each line runs in the same shell.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] You can also configure commands to run in the background if you do not want to wait for the step to complete before moving on to subsequent run steps.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For jobs that run on **Linux**, CircleCI defaults the `shell` option to `/bin/bash -eo pipefail` if `/bin/bash` exists in the build container.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Otherwise, CircleCI uses `/bin/sh -eo pipefail`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The default shell is not a login shell (CircleCI does not specify `--login` or `-l`) and thus does not source your `~/.bash_profile`, `~/.bash_login`, or `~/.profile` files.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For jobs that run on **macOS**, the default shell is `/bin/bash --login -eo pipefail`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The shell is a non-interactive login shell.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The shell executes `/etc/profile/` followed by `~/.bash_profile` before every step.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information about which files are executed when Bash is invoked, see the `INVOCATION` section of the `bash` manpage.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Descriptions of the `-eo pipefail` options are provided below.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In the previous example, `mkdir` failed to create a directory and returned a non-zero status, so the shell terminated command execution and marked the whole step as failed.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If you want the opposite behavior, add `set +e` in your `command` or override the default `shell` in your `run` configuration map.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If `pipefail` is enabled, the pipeline’s return status is the value of the last (rightmost) command to exit with a non-zero status, or zero if all commands exit successfully.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The shell waits for all commands in the pipeline to terminate before returning a value.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If `make test` fails, the `-o pipefail` option causes the whole step to fail.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Without `-o pipefail`, the step always runs successfully because the result of the whole pipeline is determined by the last command (`tee test-output.log`), which always returns a zero status.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If you want to avoid this behavior, you can specify `set +o pipefail` in the command or override the whole `shell` (see example above).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] We recommend using the default options (`-eo pipefail`) because they show errors in intermediate commands and simplify debugging job failures.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For convenience, the UI displays the used shell and all active options for each `run` step.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information, see the Using Shell Scripts document.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `background` attribute enables you to configure commands to run in the background.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Job execution proceeds to the next step rather than waiting for return of a command with the `background` attribute set to `true`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The following example shows the configuration for running the X virtual framebuffer in the background which is commonly required to run Selenium tests.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] `run` has a convenient shorthand syntax.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In this case, `command` and `name` become the string value of `run`, and the rest of the config map for that `run` have their default values.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] By default, CircleCI executes job steps one at a time, in the order you define them in `config.yml`, until a step fails (returns a non-zero exit code).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] After a command fails, no further job steps execute.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Adding the `when` attribute to a job step allows you to override this default behavior, and selectively run or skip steps depending on the status of the job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The step runs only if all previous steps succeeded (returned exit code 0).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The step runs regardless of the exit status of previous steps.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Use `always` when you have a task that must run whether previous steps succeed or fail.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For example, you need to upload logs or code-coverage data.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The step runs only if one of the preceding steps failed (returns a non-zero exit code).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Common uses of `on_fail` include storing diagnostic data to debug test failures, or running custom notifications about the failure, such as sending emails or triggering alerts.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A job can exit without failing by using `run: circleci-agent step halt`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] However, if a step within the job is already failing, the job continues to fail.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] This can be useful in situations where jobs need to conditionally execute.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Automatic reruns are only supported for `run` steps, not special steps like `checkout` or `setup_remote_docker`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information, see the Automatic Reruns page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A conditional step consists of a step with the key `when` or `unless`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Under the `when` key are the subkeys `condition` and `steps`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The purpose of the `when` step is customizing commands and job configuration to run on custom conditions (determined at config-compile time) that are checked before a workflow runs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] See the Conditional Steps Section of the Reusable Configuration Reference for more details.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A special step used to check out source code to the configured `path` (defaults to the `working_directory`).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The reason this is a special step is because it is more of a helper function designed to simplify the process of checking out code.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For GitHub OAuth, GitLab, and Bitbucket pipelines, `checkout` configures git to check out over SSH.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If you require git over HTTPS, do not use this step as it configures git to check out over SSH.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For GitHub App pipelines (GitHub Cloud and GitHub Enterprise Server), `checkout` uses HTTPS.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In the case of `checkout`, the step type is just a string with no additional attributes.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The checkout command automatically adds the required authenticity keys for interacting with GitHub and Bitbucket over SSH.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] These keys are detailed further in the Integration Guide.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] This guide is also helpful if you wish to implement a custom checkout command.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] You can specify a checkout strategy by using the `method` key.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] CircleCI supports full clones or blobless clones.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Blobless clones reduce the amount of data fetched from the remote by asking the remote to filter out objects that are not attached to the current commit.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If a downstream step requires those objects to exist for scanning or comparisons, a blobless clone can cause failures.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Allows Docker commands to be run locally.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] See Running Docker Commands for details.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Generates and stores a cache of a file or directory of files such as dependencies or source code.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Caches are stored in CircleCI’s object storage.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Learn more on the Caching Dependencies page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Cache retention can be customized on the CircleCI web app by navigating to **Usage Controls**.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The cache for a specific `key` is immutable.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If a cache already exists for the given `key`, CircleCI uses the existing cache and proceeds to the next step.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] During step execution, CircleCI replaces the templates above with runtime values and uses the resultant string as the `key`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] CircleCI regenerates the cache every time you change something in the package-lock.json file.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Different branches of this project generate the same cache key.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Same as the previous one, but each branch generates a separate cache.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Every job run generates a separate cache.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Restores a previously saved cache based on a `key`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Cache needs to have been saved first for this key using the `save_cache` step.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Learn more in The Caching Documentation.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] (1) You must specify at least one attribute.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If you provide both `key` and `keys`, CircleCI checks `key` first, then `keys`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A key is searched against existing keys as a prefix.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] In this case, CircleCI restores cache `v1-myapp-cache-new` because this is the most recent match with the `v1-myapp-cache` prefix, even though the first key (`v1-myapp-cache`) is an exact match.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information on key formatting, see the `key` section of `save_cache` step.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] When CircleCI encounters a list of `keys`, it restores the cache from the first key that matches an existing cache.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] We recommend you use a more specific key first (for example, cache for exact version of `package-lock.json`) and more generic keys after (for example, any cache for this project).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If no key matches an existing cache, CircleCI skips the step with a warning.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A path does not need to be specified here because CircleCI restores the cache to the location where it originally saved it.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If you have parallelism `> 1` in your job, see the Migrate From Deploy to Run guide.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Step to store artifacts (for example logs, binaries, etc.) to be available in the web app or through the API.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] See the Uploading Artifacts page for more information.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] There can be multiple `store_artifacts` steps in a job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Using a unique prefix for each step prevents them from overwriting files.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Artifact storage retention can be customized on the CircleCI web app by navigating to **Usage Controls**.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Special step used to upload and store test results for a build.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Test results are visible on the CircleCI web application under each build’s **Test Summary** section.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Storing test results is useful for timing analysis of your test suites.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information on storing test results, see the Collecting Test Data page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] You can also store test results as build artifacts.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For steps, refer to the `store_artifacts` step section.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Special step used to persist a temporary file to be used by another job in the workflow.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information on using workspaces, see the Using Workspaces to Share Data Between Jobs page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] `persist_to_workspace` adopts the storage settings from the storage customization controls on the CircleCI web app.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] If no custom setting is provided, `persist_to_workspace` defaults to 15 days.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Workspace storage retention can be customized on the CircleCI web app by navigating to **Usage Controls**.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The root key is a directory on the container which is taken to be the root directory of the workspace.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The path values are all relative to the root.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For example, the following step syntax persists the specified paths from `/tmp/dir` into the workspace, relative to the directory `/tmp/dir`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `paths` list uses `Glob` from Go, and the pattern matches filepath.Match.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The Go documentation states that the pattern may describe hierarchical names such as `/usr/*/bin/ed` (assuming the Separator is '/').
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Special step used to attach the workflow’s workspace to the current container.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The full contents of the workspace are downloaded and copied into the directory the workspace is being attached at.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information on using workspaces, see the Using Workspaces page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Special step that adds SSH keys from a project’s settings to a container.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information on SSH keys see the Add Additional SSH Keys page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Pipeline values are available to all pipeline configurations and can be used without previous declaration.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For a list of pipeline values, see the Pipeline Values and Parameters page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Enables jobs to go through a set of well-defined IP address ranges.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `job-groups` key lets you define named sets of jobs at the top level of your config.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A job group can be invoked in a workflow just like a regular job, and optionally serialized as an atomic unit by adding `serial-group` to the invocation.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Each job group consists of the group’s name as a key and a map as a value.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information, see the Job Groups section of the Controlling Serial Execution Across Your Organization page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Each workflow consists of the workflow name as a key and a map as a value.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] A name must be unique within the current `config.yml`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The top-level keys for the Workflows configuration are `version` and `jobs`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] For more information, see the Using Workflows to Orchestrate Jobs page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The Workflows `version` field is used to issue warnings for deprecation or breaking changes.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `max_auto_reruns` key is used to configure the maximum number of automatic reruns for a workflow.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The value of `max_auto_reruns` can be an integer between 1 and 5.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Specifies which triggers will cause this workflow to be executed.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Default behavior is to trigger the workflow when pushing to a branch.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `cron` key is defined using POSIX `crontab` syntax.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Trigger filters can have the key `branches`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The `branches` key controls whether the *current* branch has a schedule trigger created for it, where *current* branch is the branch containing the `config.yml` file with the `trigger` stanza.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] That is, a push on the `main` branch only schedules a workflow using Filters in Your Workflows for the `main` branch.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Branches can have the keys `only` and `ignore` which each map to a single string naming a branch.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] You may also use regular expressions to match against branches by enclosing them with `/’s, or map to a list of such strings.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Regular expressions must match the **entire** string.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] 1: One of either `only` or `ignore` branch filters must be specified.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] You may use a `when` clause (the inverse clause `unless` is also supported) under a workflow declaration with a logic statement to determine whether or not to run that workflow.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] The example configuration below uses a pipeline parameter, `run_integration_tests` to drive the `integration_tests` workflow.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] This example prevents the workflow `integration_tests` from running unless the pipeline is triggered on the `main` branch.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p02] Refer to the Workflows for more examples and conceptual information.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] A job can have the keys `requires`, `name`, `context`, `type`, and `filters`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] A job name that exists in your `config.yml`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `override-with` key is used to override the job configuration with a job from the referenced orb.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For more information, see the How to Override Config page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] In the example above, the `test` job in the workflow is being overridden with the orb job `my-orb/my-test`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `my-orb/my-test` job might be defined with a different resource class or execution steps.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] If the `my-orb/my-test` job is not defined inside the orb, the `test` job will compile using the local job definition.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `serial-group` key is used to add a property to a job to allow a group of jobs to run in series, rather than concurrently, across an organization.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Serial groups control the orchestration of jobs across an organization, not just within projects and pipelines.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `serial-group` key is configurable per job, or at the job group invocation level.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] To apply `serial-group` to an entire job group, see `job-groups`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The value of the `serial-group` key is a string that is used to group jobs together to run one after another.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For more information, see the Controlling Serial Execution Across Your Organization page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Jobs are run concurrently by default, so you must explicitly require any dependencies by their job name if you need some jobs to run sequentially.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `name` key can be used to invoke reusable jobs across any number of workflows.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Using the name key ensures numbers are not appended to your job name (for example, sayhello-1, sayhello-2, etc.).
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The name you assign to the `name` key needs to be unique, otherwise the numbers will still be appended to the job name.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Jobs may be configured to use global environment variables set for an organization, see the Contexts document for adding a context in the application settings.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] A job may have a `type` of `approval` indicating it must be manually approved before downstream jobs may proceed.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For more information see the Using Workflows to Orchestrate Jobs page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] In the example above the approval job is named `hold`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The name you choose for an approval job must not be used to define a job in the main configuration.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] An approval job only exists as a workflow orchestration device.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Job filters can have the keys `branches` or `tags`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] You can read more about using regular expressions in your config in the Using Workflows to Schedule Jobs page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] An expression-based job filter is a rule that is evaluated against pipeline values and parameters to decide whether a job runs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Using expression-based job filters is one way to optimize your pipelines.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The operators you can use for expression-based job filters are described in the following table.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] You can also group sub-expressions with parentheses `(`, `)` as in the examples above.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The branches filter can have the keys `only` and `ignore`, which map to a single string naming a branch.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] You may also use regular expressions to match against branches by enclosing them with slashes, or map to a list of such strings.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] CircleCI does not run workflows for tags unless you explicitly specify tag filters.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] If a job requires any other jobs (directly or indirectly), you must specify tag filters for those jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Tags can have the keys `only` and `ignore`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] You may also use regular expressions to match against tags by enclosing them with slashes, or map to a list of such strings.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Both lightweight and annotated tags are supported.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For more information, see the Executing Workflows for a Git Tag section of the Workflows page.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `matrix` stanza allows you to run a parameterized job multiple times with different arguments.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For more information see the how-to guide on Using Matrix Jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] In order to use the `matrix` stanza, you must use parameterized jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The following is a basic example of using matrix jobs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Sometimes you may wish to run a job with every combination of arguments *except* some value or values.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] To require an entire matrix (every job within the matrix), use its `alias`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The `alias` defaults to the name of the job being invoked.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] This means that `another-job` will require both deploy jobs in the matrix to finish before it runs.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Matrix jobs expose their parameter values via `<< matrix.* >>` which can be used to generate more complex workflows.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For example, here is a `deploy` matrix where each job waits for its respective `build` job in another matrix.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Every job invocation in a workflow may optionally accept two special arguments: `pre-steps` and `post-steps`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Steps under `pre-steps` are executed before any of the other steps in the job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The steps under `post-steps` are executed after all of the other steps.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Pre and post steps allow you to execute steps in a given job without modifying the job.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Pre and post steps are useful, for example, to run custom setup steps before job execution.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Certain dynamic configuration features accept logic statements as arguments.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Logic statements are evaluated to boolean values at configuration compilation time, that is, before the workflow is run.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Also note that using logic with an empty list will cause a validation error.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Logic statements always evaluate to a boolean value at the top level, and coerce as necessary.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] They can be nested in an arbitrary fashion, according to their argument specifications, and to a maximum depth of 100 levels.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] `matches` uses Java regular expressions for its `pattern`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] A full match pattern must be provided, prefix matching is not an option.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] It is recommended to enclose a pattern in `^` and `$` to avoid accidental partial matches.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] CircleCI configuration supports expressions for dynamic value evaluation.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Expressions can include pipeline values, pipeline parameters, literals, and operators such as `and`, `or`, and comparison operators.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Configuration fields accept expressions either directly or as string values.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] When you provide a string value, you can use `<< >>` delimiters to mark a section of the string to be interpreted as an expression.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] In this example, `parallelism` is set to `10` when running on the `main` branch, and `1` on all other branches.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] Use direct expressions in job filters and using `when` or `unless` in your workflows.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] For all other configuration fields, you must use the `<< >>` delimiters to mark the expression as an expression, as shown in other examples in this section.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] In this example, the `<< >>` delimiters mark `pipeline.git.branch or "unknown branch"` as an expression.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] If `pipeline.git.branch` is null (for example, when the pipeline is triggered for a tag rather than a branch), the `or` operator provides the fallback value "unknown branch".
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] The operators you can use for expressions are described in the following table.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] You can also group sub-expressions with parentheses `(`, `)`.
[src:circleci/configuration-reference-p03] You can find usage examples on the Orchestration Cookbook page.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:circleci/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:circleci/getting-started] This quickstart provides a guided tour through setting up a project, collaborating, and tools to iterate on and debug your build configuration.
[src:circleci/getting-started] If you would rather jump to a full list of CircleCI `config.yml` options, see the Configuration Reference.
[src:circleci/getting-started] Select **Projects** from the sidebar and locate your project from the list.
[src:circleci/getting-started] Select the ellipsis menu (Ellipsis menu icon)(Ellipsis menu icon) next to your project and select **Project Settings**.
[src:circleci/getting-started] The project slug is listed on the project settings homepage.
[src:circleci/getting-started] **GitHub App**: Project slug starts with `circleci` followed by UUIDs.
[src:circleci/getting-started] For example, `circleci/34R3kN5RtfEE7v4sa4nWAU/4nYdoKGkb6RXn7JGt8SQtg`.
[src:circleci/getting-started] **GitHub OAuth app**: Project slug is human readable.
[src:circleci/getting-started] For example, `github/circleci/circleci-demo-workflows`.
[src:circleci/getting-started] For more information about the differences, see the Version Control Systems, Pipeline Types, and Feature Support guide.
[src:circleci/getting-started] If you do not see these options select the CircleCI logo in the top bar to get back to your user homepage and check you have the correct org selected.
[src:circleci/getting-started] For a more detailed look at this process see the Create a Project guide.
[src:circleci/getting-started] Review your project details and select **Commit config and run**.
[src:circleci/getting-started] In the next sections we will cover ways to modify and debug your config.
[src:circleci/getting-started] If you do not see these options, select the CircleCI logo in the top bar to get back to your user homepage and check you have the correct org selected.
[src:circleci/page] Use the tutorials, samples, how-to, and reference documentation to learn CircleCI.
[src:circleci/page] Get started in minutes: follow step-by-step guides or explore a sample app.
[src:circleci/page] Trigger pipelines from your VCS, API, and the CircleCI app.
[src:circleci/page] Create and configure jobs to deploy to AWS, GCP, and more.
[src:circleci/page] Build Docker images and execute your jobs in Docker environments.
[src:circleci/page] Easily integrate third-party tools using certified and partner orbs.
[src:circleci/page] Create and manage contexts in the CircleCI app.
[src:circleci/page] View and manage your deployments from a single dashboard.
[src:circleci/page] Gain immediate visibility into org wide deployments.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:circleci/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
